          "body": "Joseph names the *telos* of God's sending three ways: *to preserve life* (45:5, *michyah*), *to preserve for you a remnant in the earth* (45:7, *sheerit*), *to keep you alive by a great deliverance* (45:7, *peletah gedolah*). The vocabulary is the prophets' vocabulary of eschatological salvation — Isaiah 10:20-22 on the *sheerit* of Israel, Joel 2:32 on the *peletah* on Mount Zion. Genesis 45 is the seedbed of remnant theology. The covenant family of seventy persons (46:27) is the *sheerit* through whom Abraham's promise (Genesis 12:1-3) will become the nation Israel and ultimately the Messiah (Matthew 1:1-17). Joseph's twenty-two years of suffering preserved the line through which redemption would come. His suffering had a salvific function — he was sent ahead, alone, to absorb what would otherwise have destroyed the family. The typological resonance with Christ is not strained; it is structurally embedded in the text."
